                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 1.  <span>Distribution of gene gain and loss among mammalian lineages. </span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1"></a><p>Numbers in parentheses report number of genes gained or lost on each branch.</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p2" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p2"></a><p>Pie charts near branches show the proportion of families that expanded (green), contracted (red), or did not change (blue).</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p3" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p3"></a><p>The large pie chart shows the proportion of all families that change (orange), or remain constant (blue) across all lineages.</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p4" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec1.fig1.caption1.p4"></a><p>Changes along long branches and on the ingroup branch may represent underestimates due to multiple gains and losses within individual families and or lack of phylogenetic resolution.</p>
